[normal]3.0[bold]              [bold]Taking into Account Groups of Passenger with Different Needs[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1
[normal]              
[normal]The approach described above is well defined and has good structure and clear and intended outcomes. However in the absence of active and positive participation 
[normal]f
[normal]r
[normal]o
[normal]m local communitie
[normal]s 
[normal]the approach will not yield results 
[normal]or
[normal] 
[normal]lead to 
[normal]the implementation of solutions that reflect local needs. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2
[normal]              
[normal]A
[normal] comprehensive stakeholder analysis and mapping exercise has identified six main groups that will be key to community engagement for this project.  Local engagement plans will provide more detail on an area basis and explore the mechanisms that can be used
[normal] to engage with each of these groups and their sub-sections.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Communities
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is not a one size fits all approach to community engagement
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]W
[normal]ithin Cambridgeshire there is considerable diversity between each local community that will determine the most appropriate approach to engagement.  When working with communities it 
[normal]is 
[normal]recognised that there may already be groups and networks of active peopl
[normal]e that could play an important role on the engagement process. In addition to this consideration will also be given to the two main forms of engagement;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Communities of place[bold] – 
[normal]formed from
[normal] residents who live in an area where services are being reviewed.  T
[normal]here are two key audiences within this group. Those who currently use buses and those who 
[normal]have the potential
[normal] 
[normal]to
[normal] use services
[normal] in the future
[normal]. The success of the project will depend on engaging with these two groups.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Communities of interest [bold]– 
[normal]formed from tho
[normal]se with a shared interest in the provision of transport in an area. 
[normal]There
[normal] 
[normal]communities 
[normal]may be made up from interest groups such as
[normal] ‘Save our buses’ part of the campaign for better transport or ‘Towards Sustainability’, they could also be businesses within t
[normal]he area.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Members
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Lack of member buy-in is 
[normal]a 
[normal]key risk. The withdrawal of bus subsidy is a contentious issue
[normal]. 
[normal]The engagement process needs to move on quickly from these discussions to allow all stakeholders to engage positively in the development of alter
[normal]native solutions. We intend to mitigate this key risk by working closely with both District and County members drawing on their invaluable experience of the local area to help us fully understand local n
[normal]eed, to work with CCC to organis
[normal]e engagement events a
[normal]nd for members to be involved in the design of any new transport solutions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Parish Councils
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.7
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Although parish council’s have a wide range of powers there are few statutory duties placed upon them.  Parish plans may already have 
[normal]considered transport need
[normal] for a village and identified actions. These are a valuable source of information. The knowledge and experience of a parish council will enable the formation of working groups and ensure the most difficult to reach are included in the process.  The parish 
[normal]council will also have access to those who are active in the community and can help to communicate the aims of the project.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.8
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The potential assistance and support that a parish council can provide to the project should not be underestimated.  Parish councils should be involved from the outset of the project moving into an area. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.9
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Where the engagement has been at its best, there have been local champions who are driving the process forwards. In some areas the local champions have been local politicians form the county, district or parish council 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Partners
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.10
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A
[normal] number of partners 
[normal]have
[normal] been identified that will become involved over the course of the project. T
[normal]his will include organisations that currently commission transport such as PCT (GP Clusters) or are involved in transport issues such as ACRE
[normal] (Action for Communities in Rural Engla
[normal]nd)
[normal]. 
[normal] L
[normal]ocal employers, schools and the 
[normal]further education 
[normal]sector
[normal] will also be approached to become involved in the process
[normal].  The stakeholder management plan identifies how we plan to work with these organi
[normal]s
[normal]ations.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.11
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]C
[normal]ambridgeshire 
[normal]C
[normal]ounty Council a
[normal]lready has 
[normal]strong links with District Councils and they have been involved in 
[normal]Cambridgeshire Future Transport Programme
[normal] from its inception
[normal]. T
[normal]his partnership working 
[normal]is continuing
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.12
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Transport providers including 
[normal]Community Transport Schemes, Car Scheme, Commercial oper
[normal]ators, Taxi firms, Entrepreneurs and Communities or parishes which provide their own transport
[normal] also form part of this group
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Interest Groups
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.13
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is a wide range of groups who represent residents with an interest in passenger transport. Broadly these a
[normal]re;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Internal
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.14
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Internal stakeholders can be split into four distinct groups
[normal];
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]A key 
[normal]element of CFT is
[normal] 
[normal]encouraging
[normal] local communities and service providers including partners to become more involved in the proc
[normal]ess of designing and delivering transport, developing a culture of co-production. 
[normal]This moves away 
[normal]from 
[normal]the historic approach whereby subsidised services have been designed based on previous or existing provision.
[normal] 
[normal]The first step is 
[normal]work
[normal]ing
[normal] with local communities to 
[normal]asses
[normal] the transport need in their local area to then work with transport providers and the local authority to design transport solutions that best reflect the identified need.
[normal] 
[normal]By encouraging community involvement throughout the p
[normal]rocess and broadening the reach to include potential passengers, as well as existing, the resulting transport will be more sustainable and appropriate.  
